placename.","Irish: adoption for   Mulligan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mullineaux","meanings":["Irish and English (Lancashire): variant of   Molyneux  ."]},{"name":"Mulliner","meanings":["English: occupational name for a miller, from Old French <i>molinier</i> ‘miller’. Compare   Molyneux  ."]},{"name":"Molineaux","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Staffordshire): variant of   Molyneux  ."]},{"name":"Molyneaux","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): variant of   Molyneux  . Compare   Mallonee  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard de Molyneux was born in 1159, in Sefton, Lancashire, England, his father, Robert De Molyneux Lord Sefton, was 24 and his mother, Beatrice de Villers, was 21. He married Edith Pincerna Le Boteler about 1181, in Sefton, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1211, in Little Crosby, Lancashire, England, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1159–1211":"1159–1211","1161–1212":"1161–1212","1163–Male":"1163–Surnud","1165–Male":"1165–Surnud","1163–1187":"1163–1187","1183–Male":"1183–Surnud","1185–1246":"1185–1246","1187–Male":"1187–Surnud","1135–1168":"1135–1168","1138–1165":"1138–1165","about 1183":"umbes 1183","about 1181":"umbes 1181","1165":"1165","1187":"1187","1185":"1185","1163":"1163","1183":"1183","1161":"1161","1138":"1138","1159":"1159","1246":"1246","1168":"1168","1135":"1135","1212":"1212","1211":"1211","about 1187":"umbes 1187","Europe":"Europe","Warrington, Lancashire, England":"Warrington, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sefton, Lancashire, England":"Sefton, Lancashire, England","Little Crosby, Lancashire, England":"Little Crosby, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1159–1211":"1159–1211","1161–1212":"1161–1212","1163–Male":"1163–Kuollut","1165–Male":"1165–Kuollut","1163–1187":"1163–1187","1183–Male":"1183–Kuollut","1185–1246":"1185–1246","1187–Male":"1187–Kuollut","1135–1168":"1135–1168","1138–1165":"1138–1165","about 1183":"noin 1183","about 1181":"noin 1181","1165":"1165","1187":"1187","1185":"1185","1163":"1163","1183":"1183","1161":"1161","1138":"1138","1159":"1159","1246":"1246","1168":"1168","1135":"1135","1212":"1212","1211":"1211","about 1187":"noin 1187","Europe":"Europe","Warrington, Lancashire, England":"Warrington, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Sefton, Lancashire, England":"Sefton, Lancashire, England","Little Crosby, Lancashire, England":"Little Crosby, Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"1159–1211":"1159–1211","1161–12